Let $\omega = e^{2\pi i/3}$ denote the cube root of unity, and let $a$ be the position vector of $A$ in $\mathbb{C}^3$. Then $B$ and $C$ are given by $B = a\omega$ and $C = a\omega^2$. Let $p$ and $q$ be the position vectors of $P$ and $Q$, respectively, so that $|p - a| = |p - b| = |p - c| = d$ and $|q - a| = |q - b| = |q - c| = d$.

We claim that $p$ and $q$ are given by $p = a + d(u + v)$ and $q = a + d(u + w)$, where $u$, $v$, and $w$ are the normalized eigenvectors of the matrix
\[\begin{pmatrix}
0 & 1 & 1 \\
1 & 0 & 1 \\
1 & 1 & 0
\end{pmatrix}\]with eigenvalues $1$, $1$, and $-2$, respectively. Indeed, let $O$ be the circumcenter of $\triangle ABC$, so that $a$, $b$, $c$, and $O$ are coplanar. Then $p$ and $q$ must lie on the two lines which are parallel to the plane of $\triangle ABC$ and pass through $P$ and $Q$, respectively. These lines are given by $p = a + t(u + v)$ and $q = a + t(u + w)$ for some $t$, so we only need to determine $t = d$.

